            "@type": "dctypes:Text",
            "format": "text/html",
            "chars": "<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>LD.X.R2</em></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Mrs Gowan&rsquo;s pretext [...]</strong></p>\n<p><span id=\"docs-internal-guid-c1ccc0f8-7fff-dde7-915e-5cae548bb2f9\">&nbsp;</span></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Again, we see possible evidence of prospective planning in Dickens&rsquo;s direction to &ldquo;Open with this.&rdquo; The chapter indeed opens with Mrs. Gowan &ldquo;[R]esigning herself to inevitable fate&rdquo; and recognizing the benefits of the marriage between Henry and Pet, not least of which is the fact that &ldquo;Henry&rsquo;s debts must clearly be paid down upon the alter-railing by his father-in-law&rdquo; (LD 380). The conference between these two women as to the suitability of the marriage helps Dickens establish the memoranda he made and emphasized on the left-hand-side: &ldquo;Society&rsquo;s idea of a marriage.&rdquo; Mrs. Merdle &ldquo;(speaking as a Priestess of Society)&rdquo; in effect authorizes the marriage (386).</p>"
        }
